ce:section.ce:para:
To evaluate the applicability of the Fe,Cu-CD-based dual-mode sensing platform for practical analysis, this study employed standard addition methods to detect phenol and dimethoate in real samples. Table 1
                         presents the results for the detection of phenol in tap and river water samples using a colorimetric method. The recoveries ranged from 89.6 % to 114 %, whereas the relative standard deviations (RSDs) varied from 0.362 % to 7.66 %. For the fluorescent method, the recoveries of dimethoate from tap water, river water, cabbage, and garlic chives fell within the range of 90.0 %–110 %, with the corresponding RSDs between 0.745 % and 5.18 % (see Table 2
                        ). The concentrations of phenol and dimethoate in the original samples were below the detection limits of the method, which were lower than the maximum levels defined by Chinese standards, i.e., 0.1 mg/L for phenol in surface water (GB 3838-2002) and 0.006 mg/L and 0.01 mg/kg for dimethoate in drinking water (GB 5749–2022) and green leafy vegetables (GB 2763–2021). Furthermore, the favorable recoveries indicate that the proposed dual-mode colorimetric and fluorometric detection system based on Fe/Cu-CDs is suitable for detecting phenol and dimethoate in actual samples.
